This paper proposes an extension of logic programming (LP) that involves causal justifications represented as algebraic expressions. The paper discusses the relationship between these justifications and default negation, which suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also deals with the well-founded semantics of LP, which is related to logic and computation (cs.LO). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of rules and conditions, which are relevant to programming languages (cs.PL) and databases (cs.DB). Finally, the paper deals with causal relationships, which are relevant to computer engineering (cs.CE).
